reviews.review_text:
one of the great ones How strange for what could arguably be called the best show of the tour happen so late in the tour.  First set Aiko is speedier than usual but rocks more as a result.  A very swinging version with Bob providing extra oomph in his backing vocal.  An unusual pause before Minglewood which is breakneck like it was in Portland and the Peggy-O is just as good as the (what I consider to be) classic from the same Portland show (I love the scrolling through the guitar sounds Jerry does in the lead but again, that’s another show).  It’s this twelve minute Birdsong though that really makes you stand up and take notice.  A precursor to the journey the band would provide through the cosmos that is the second set, this Birdsong goes to Mars and back (during the Playin’ some of you might get stranded there) and Bob ups the ante with one of the better Supplication jams that this time moves without a hitch into a Let it Grow that’s as involved as they come, another nearly twelve minute ride.   Don’t Ease is a surprise bonus.  The Uncle John’s is one of the best versions, sparkling right out of the gate and again, featuring a solid and enthusiastic vocal performance from Bobby.  It’s unfortunate that when I think of ’86 PITB’s, I automatically think of the disaster in RFK but the ones from the spring really are worth checking out.  This one ends up in a barren Martian landscape that leads to the even more emotionally bare Brent song, a particularly solid version until it becomes clear that Brent is very drunk and distraught.  Here’s another precursor, this time to the unhinged Brent show later in the spring at BCT.  This soundboard is really special too.   The lack of cassette generation really matters and the fact that the show is strong also makes this a must hear.  Drums mercifully takes over after Brent allows the song to end drizzle to a conclusion.   It's a show that hits all the emotional highs and lows for sure.  A strong post-drums closes it.  NFA was still riding that 1985 wave and everyone clapped and chanted 
on the way out the door.
